cal context. It looks at the extensive debate within the radical press over how to situate radical values within an evolving media ecology, debates that engaged some of the most famous writers of the era (William Morris and George Bernard Shaw), a host of lesser-known figures (theosophical socialist and birth control reformer Annie Besant, gay rights pioneer Edward Carpenter, and proto-modernist editor Alfred Orage), and countless anonymous others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxPolitical aspects. 0aJournalismxPolitical aspectszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aMass mediazGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aPress and politicszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aPrintingzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aRadicalism and the presszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804784658zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804784658423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804784658.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles